{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Before downloading Git, check if it's already installed. Open your terminal (Mac/Linux) or Command Prompt (Windows) and type `git --version`. If you see a version number, Git is ready — skip to the last step.",
      "title": "Check for Existing Git"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open your web browser and go to **git-scm.com**. This is the official Git website. You should see a download button on the homepage that automatically detects your operating system.",
      "title": "Go to git-scm.com"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the **Download** button on the homepage. Your browser will start downloading the installer file. On Mac, this is a `.dmg` file. On Windows, it's a `.exe` file. On Linux, follow the package manager instructions shown.",
      "title": "Download the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "On **Windows**: locate the downloaded `.exe` file and double-click it. Click **Yes** if prompted by User Account Control. On **Mac**: open the `.dmg` file and follow the prompts. On **Linux**: run the command shown on the site for your distro.",
      "title": "Run the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "On Windows, the installer will show several option screens. Click **Next** on each screen to accept the recommended defaults. These defaults work well for most users. Click **Install** on the final confirmation screen.",
      "title": "Accept Default Options"
    },
    {
      "text": "Wait for the progress bar to complete. On Windows, click **Finish** when the installer is done. On Mac, you may be asked to enter your system password — type it and press Enter to authorize the installation.",
      "title": "Complete the Installation"
    },
    {
      "text": "Close and reopen your terminal or Command Prompt. Type `git --version` and press Enter. You should see output like `git version 2.x.x`. This confirms Git is installed and accessible from your command line.",
      "title": "Verify the Installation"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Before doing anything else, turn on your hazard lights. This alerts other drivers. If possible, move your vehicle to a flat, stable surface away from traffic — a parking lot or wide shoulder is ideal.",
      "title": "Move to a Safe Location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open your trunk and locate the spare tire, jack, and lug wrench. These are usually stored under the trunk floor mat. Confirm all three are present before proceeding.",
      "title": "Gather Your Equipment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the wheel wedges or large rocks and place them in front of or behind the tires that are NOT being changed. This prevents the car from rolling while it's lifted.",
      "title": "Secure the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Using the lug wrench, turn each lug nut **counterclockwise** about half a turn. Don't remove them yet — just loosen them while the tire is still on the ground. You should feel them break free.",
      "title": "Loosen the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check your owner's manual for the jack points — reinforced areas under the vehicle frame near each tire. Positioning the jack incorrectly can damage your car or cause it to slip.",
      "title": "Find the Jack Point"
    },
    {
      "text": "Slide the jack under the vehicle at the correct jack point. Turn the jack handle clockwise to raise it until it makes firm contact with the frame. It should feel solid, not wobbly.",
      "title": "Position the Jack"
    },
    {
      "text": "Continue turning the jack handle clockwise to raise the vehicle. Lift until the flat tire is about **6 inches off the ground**. Do not place any part of your body under the vehicle.",
      "title": "Raise the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Now fully remove each lug nut by turning counterclockwise. Place them somewhere safe — your pocket or a small bag works well. You'll need all of them to mount the spare.",
      "title": "Remove the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grip the flat tire with both hands and pull it straight toward you. It may feel stuck — wiggle it gently side to side to break the seal. Set it flat on the ground out of your way.",
      "title": "Pull Off the Flat Tire"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "You'll need a French press, coarsely ground coffee, a kettle, filtered water, a timer, and a mug. Coarse grounds are key — they should look like rough sea salt. Fine grounds will make your coffee bitter and hard to press.",
      "title": "Gather Your Equipment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Heat water to about **200°F (93°C)** — just off boiling. If you don't have a thermometer, bring water to a boil, then let it sit for 30 seconds. You should see steam but no active bubbling.",
      "title": "Heat the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour a small amount of hot water into the empty French press and swirl it around. Then discard the water. This warms the glass and helps maintain your brewing temperature.",
      "title": "Preheat the French Press"
    },
    {
      "text": "Add **1 tablespoon (7g) of coarse coffee grounds per 4 oz of water** to the French press. For a standard 12 oz cup, use about 3 tablespoons. Use a scale for precision if you have one.",
      "title": "Measure Your Coffee Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Start your timer and slowly pour hot water over the grounds until they're fully submerged. Fill to about 1 inch below the top. You should see the grounds bloom — puff up slightly as gas is released.",
      "title": "Add the Hot Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Using a spoon, gently stir the grounds and water together for about 5 seconds. This ensures all grounds are evenly saturated. You should see a uniform mixture with no dry clumps floating on top.",
      "title": "Stir the Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the lid on the French press with the plunger pulled all the way up. Do not press yet. Let the coffee steep for exactly **4 minutes**. Watch your timer — under-steeping makes weak coffee, over-steeping makes it bitter.",
      "title": "Place the Lid and Steep"
    },
    {
      "text": "When the timer hits 4 minutes, grip the handle firmly and press the plunger down **slowly and steadily**. It should take about 20–30 seconds to reach the bottom. If it pushes too easily, your grind is too coarse.",
      "title": "Press the Plunger Down"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour your coffee into a mug **immediately** after pressing. Don't let it sit in the French press — the grounds will continue to steep and turn the coffee bitter within a few minutes.",
      "title": "Pour Right Away"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take a sip and evaluate. Bitter? Grind coarser next time or reduce steep time. Weak or sour? Grind finer or steep longer. Small adjustments make a big difference — note what you changed for next time.",
      "title": "Taste and Adjust"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Gather your tools before starting: a spade or garden fork, a rake, a soil thermometer, compost or aged manure, and a pH testing kit. Lay them near the garden bed so everything is within reach.",
      "title": "Gather Your Tools"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a string line or garden hose to outline your bed. Tomatoes need space — aim for a bed at least 4 feet wide and 8 feet long. Mark the corners with stakes so the boundary is clear.",
      "title": "Mark the Garden Bed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Insert your soil thermometer 4 inches into the ground. Tomatoes need soil at least **60°F** to thrive. If it reads below that, wait a few days and check again before proceeding.",
      "title": "Check Soil Temperature"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push your spade or garden fork straight down about 12 inches into the soil. Work your way across the entire bed, breaking up the earth in rows. This loosens compaction and improves drainage.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove any rocks, roots, or debris you uncover as you dig. Toss them into a bucket beside you. You should end up with a cleared, broken-up bed with no large obstructions visible.",
      "title": "Clear Rocks and Debris"
    },
    {
      "text": "Insert the pH test strip or probe into the moist soil and wait for the reading. Tomatoes prefer a pH of **6.0–6.8**. Note the reading — you'll use it to decide which amendments to add.",
      "title": "Test the Soil pH"
    },
    {
      "text": "If pH is below 6.0, spread **1 cup of garden lime** per 10 sq ft and work it in. If above 6.8, add **elemental sulfur** per package directions. Skip this step if your reading is already in range.",
      "title": "Adjust Soil pH"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread a 3-inch layer of compost or aged manure evenly across the entire bed. Use a shovel to distribute it uniformly. You should see a consistent dark layer covering the surface before mixing.",
      "title": "Add Compost or Manure"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use your garden fork to work the compost into the top 10–12 inches of soil. Turn and mix thoroughly until the amendment is fully blended in. The soil should look uniformly dark and crumbly.",
      "title": "Mix Amendments Into Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull your rake across the bed in long, even strokes to level the surface. Break up any remaining clumps. The finished bed should be smooth, level, and have a fine, loose texture — ready for planting.",
      "title": "Rake the Surface Smooth"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Gather your fabric, sewing pattern or measurements, fabric scissors, straight pins, a fabric marker or chalk, a ruler or measuring tape, and a flat cutting surface like a table or cutting mat.",
      "title": "Gather Your Supplies"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay your fabric flat on your cutting surface, wrong side up. Smooth out all wrinkles with your hands. Wrinkled fabric leads to inaccurate cuts — take your time here.",
      "title": "Lay Out Your Fabric"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fold the fabric in half lengthwise so the selvage edges (the finished edges) line up evenly. Press the fold flat with your hand. This lets you cut two matching pieces at once.",
      "title": "Fold the Fabric in Half"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check your pattern or measurements. A standard pillowcase needs one piece 27\" × 21\" for the body and one piece 27\" × 9\" for the cuff. Write down your measurements before marking.",
      "title": "Check Your Measurements"
    },
    {
      "text": "Using your ruler and fabric marker or chalk, measure and mark the cutting lines directly on the fabric. Draw clearly visible lines so your cuts will be straight and accurate.",
      "title": "Mark the Cutting Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place straight pins every 3–4 inches along the marked lines, pinning through both layers of fabric. Pins should run parallel to the cutting line. This keeps the layers from shifting while you cut.",
      "title": "Pin Along the Cutting Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pick up your fabric scissors — not paper scissors, which will dull them. Hold the scissors comfortably and keep the lower blade sliding along the cutting surface for the straightest cut.",
      "title": "Pick Up Your Fabric Scissors"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cut smoothly along your marked lines using long, steady strokes. Don't lift the fabric off the table as you cut. Follow the line exactly — avoid jagged or angled cuts.",
      "title": "Cut Along the Marked Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the pins as you go or after cutting. Separate the two cut layers and hold them up side by side. They should match in size. If one is noticeably larger, re-measure and trim the difference.",
      "title": "Remove Pins and Check Pieces"
    },
    {
      "text": "Stack your cut fabric pieces neatly and set them aside. You should have your pillowcase body and cuff pieces ready. Your fabric is now prepped and ready for the next sewing step.",
      "title": "Set Aside the Cut Pieces"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "You'll need your guitar and a way to hear reference pitches. Use a clip-on tuner, a free tuning app like GuitarTuna, or a piano/keyboard. Make sure you're in a quiet space so you can hear each string clearly.",
      "title": "Gather Your Tools"
    },
    {
      "text": "If using a clip-on tuner, attach it to the headstock (the top of the guitar neck). If using an app, open it and grant microphone permission. The tuner will detect vibrations or sound from your strings.",
      "title": "Set Up Your Tuner"
    },
    {
      "text": "Standard tuning has 6 strings: **E A D G B e** from thickest to thinnest. The thickest string (closest to your chin) is low **E**. The thinnest (closest to the floor) is high **e**. You'll tune them in this order.",
      "title": "Learn the String Order"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thickest string (6th string) firmly with your thumb or a pick. Let it ring out. Your tuner should display a note name. If nothing appears, pluck again a little harder.",
      "title": "Pluck the 6th String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at your tuner's display. The needle or indicator should point to **E**. If it's flat (too low), the needle leans left. If it's sharp (too high), it leans right. Center means in tune.",
      "title": "Read the Tuner Display"
    },
    {
      "text": "Find the tuning peg for the 6th string on the headstock. Turn it slowly — small turns make a big difference. If flat, tighten the string. If sharp, loosen it. Pluck again after each small adjustment.",
      "title": "Turn the Tuning Peg"
    },
    {
      "text": "Keep adjusting and replucking until the tuner needle is centered on **E** and the display shows green (or similar confirmation). The string is now in tune. Repeat this process for each remaining string.",
      "title": "Center the Needle on E"
    },
    {
      "text": "Move to the 5th string (A). Pluck it, read the tuner, and adjust the peg until the display shows **A** and the needle is centered. Take your time — small, slow turns are easier to control.",
      "title": "Tune the 5th String to A"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 4th string (D). Adjust the tuning peg until the tuner shows **D** centered. Then move to the 3rd string (G) and repeat, aiming for a centered **G** on the display.",
      "title": "Tune 4th (D) and 3rd (G)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 2nd string and tune it to **B**. Then pluck the thinnest string (1st string) and tune it to high **e**. These two strings are easier to accidentally over-tighten — turn the pegs especially slowly.",
      "title": "Tune 2nd (B) and 1st (e)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tuning one string can slightly pull others out. Strum all 6 strings once, then quickly check each string on the tuner again. If any drifted, fine-tune them now until all 6 read in tune.",
      "title": "Do a Final Check"
    },
    {
      "text": "Strum an open E major chord (frets: x-2-2-1-0-0) and listen. It should sound clear and resonant, not buzzy or off. If it sounds right, your guitar is in tune and ready to play!",
      "title": "Test With a Chord"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Before adjusting exposure, switch your camera to **Manual (M)** mode using the mode dial on top. This gives you full control over ISO, aperture, and shutter speed. If you don't see an M, look for a dial with letters like P, A, S, M.",
      "title": "Switch to Manual Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Point your camera at your scene and look through the viewfinder or at the LCD screen. Find the **exposure meter** — a horizontal scale with a zero in the center. This tells you if your scene is over- or underexposed.",
      "title": "Check the Exposure Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the **ISO button** (labeled ISO on the body or in the menu). Set ISO to **100** as your starting point. Use this in bright light. You should see the ISO value update on the display. Lower ISO = less grain.",
      "title": "Set Your ISO First"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the **aperture control** — usually the front dial. Set it to **f/8** as a neutral starting point. You'll see the f-number change on the display. A higher f-number means a smaller opening and more of the scene in focus.",
      "title": "Set Your Aperture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Find the **shutter speed control** — usually the rear dial. Set it to **1/125s** as a baseline. You'll see the fraction update on the display. Faster speeds freeze motion; slower speeds blur it.",
      "title": "Set Your Shutter Speed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at the exposure meter again. If the marker sits *left of zero*, your shot is underexposed — increase ISO or widen the aperture (lower f-number). If it's *right of zero*, decrease ISO or raise shutter speed.",
      "title": "Read the Exposure Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take a **test shot** by pressing the shutter button fully. Review the image on your LCD screen. Check both the brightness and the **histogram** if available — a good exposure shows the graph spread across the middle without clipping either edge.",
      "title": "Take a Test Shot"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the image is too dark, try one change at a time: lower shutter speed to **1/60s**, widen aperture to **f/5.6**, or raise ISO to **400**. Recheck the meter and take another test shot after each adjustment.",
      "title": "Correct an Underexposed Shot"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the image is too bright, raise shutter speed to **1/250s**, narrow aperture to **f/11**, or lower ISO to **100**. Make one change at a time and retake the shot. The meter marker should move toward zero.",
      "title": "Correct an Overexposed Shot"
    },
    {
      "text": "Once your test shot looks balanced — natural brightness, no blown-out highlights, visible shadows — your exposure is set. The histogram should form a hill shape without data pushed hard against either edge.",
      "title": "Confirm Proper Exposure"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Stand near a wall or sturdy chair in case you need balance support. Wear flat-soled shoes or go barefoot — avoid cushioned running shoes, which can throw off your alignment.",
      "title": "Gather Your Equipment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place your feet shoulder-width apart, toes pointing slightly outward (about 10–15 degrees). Look down — your feet should be directly under your shoulders. This is your starting stance.",
      "title": "Set Your Foot Position"
    },
    {
      "text": "Stand tall, shoulders back and down, chest up. Engage your core by bracing your abs as if you're about to take a punch. Keep your spine neutral — no arch or rounding.",
      "title": "Align Your Upper Body"
    },
    {
      "text": "Extend both arms straight out in front of you at shoulder height, palms facing down. This counterbalances your weight as you descend and helps you stay upright.",
      "title": "Raise Your Arms"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push your hips back first — like you're reaching for a chair behind you. Then bend your knees, tracking them in line with your second toe. Start slowly.",
      "title": "Begin the Descent"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lower until your thighs are parallel to the floor (or as low as comfortable). Check that your knees aren't caving inward and your heels remain flat on the ground.",
      "title": "Reach the Bottom Position"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at your knees — they should be over your toes, not collapsed inward. Your chest should stay lifted. If your heels lift, widen your stance slightly and try again.",
      "title": "Check Your Knee Alignment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Drive through your heels to stand back up. Squeeze your glutes at the top and straighten your hips fully. You should feel your quads and glutes working, not your lower back.",
      "title": "Drive Back Up"
    },
    {
      "text": "At the top, check that you're fully upright — hips and knees completely extended, core still engaged. Avoid leaning forward or hyperextending your lower back.",
      "title": "Verify Full Extension"
    },
    {
      "text": "Perform 5 slow reps, pausing 2 seconds at the bottom each time. Focus on form, not speed. If you feel knee pain or your heels lift, stop and recheck your foot width and depth.",
      "title": "Practice 5 Reps with Pauses"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Separe: 500g de farinha de trigo, 10g de fermento biológico seco, 10g de sal, 15g de açúcar, 300ml de água morna e 30ml de óleo. Coloque todos os ingredientes na bancada antes de começar.",
      "title": "Separe os ingredientes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Meça 300ml de água entre 35°C e 40°C — deve estar morna ao toque, não quente. Use um termômetro culinário ou teste com o pulso: a água não deve queimar a pele.",
      "title": "Aqueça a água corretamente"
    },
    {
      "text": "Despeje a água morna em uma tigela pequena. Adicione 10g de fermento biológico seco e 15g de açúcar. Misture levemente com uma colher e aguarde 10 minutos sem mexer.",
      "title": "Ative o fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Após 10 minutos, o fermento deve estar espumoso e com bolhas na superfície. Se não houver espuma, o fermento pode estar vencido — descarte e repita com fermento novo.",
      "title": "Verifique a ativação"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela grande, coloque 500g de farinha de trigo e 10g de sal. Misture com uma colher para distribuir o sal uniformemente antes de adicionar os líquidos.",
      "title": "Misture os ingredientes secos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Faça um buraco no centro da farinha. Despeje a mistura de fermento ativado e os 30ml de óleo dentro do buraco. Comece a misturar com uma colher, puxando a farinha das bordas para o centro.",
      "title": "Adicione os líquidos à farinha"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando a massa começar a se soltar das paredes da tigela e formar uma bola, transfira para uma superfície enfarinhada. A massa deve estar ligeiramente pegajosa, mas não grudenta em excesso.",
      "title": "Transfira a massa para a bancada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pressione a massa com a palma da mão, dobre ao meio e gire 90°. Repita esse movimento por 10 minutos sem parar. A massa está no ponto certo quando estiver lisa, elástica e não grudar nas mãos.",
      "title": "Sove a massa por 10 minutos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Faça uma bolinha com a massa e pressione com o dedo. Se a massa voltar lentamente ao formato original, o glúten está bem desenvolvido e a sova está completa.",
      "title": "Teste o ponto da massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Unte levemente uma tigela com óleo, coloque a massa dentro e cubra com um pano úmido ou plástico filme. A massa está pronta para descansar e crescer na etapa seguinte.",
      "title": "Cubra a massa para descansar"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Busca las llaves de paso debajo del fregadero o cerca de la pared. Gíralas en sentido horario hasta que queden completamente cerradas. Abre el grifo para confirmar que ya no sale agua.",
      "title": "Cierra el suministro de agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pon el tapón en el desagüe del fregadero para evitar que las piezas pequeñas caigan. Coloca una toalla debajo del grifo para absorber el agua que quede en las tuberías.",
      "title": "Protege el área de trabajo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa un cuchillo plano o palillo para retirar la tapa decorativa en la parte superior de la manija. Debajo encontrarás un tornillo. Retíralo con un desarmador Phillips o plano según corresponda.",
      "title": "Retira la tapa y el tornillo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Jala la manija hacia arriba con firmeza para separarla del cuerpo del grifo. Si está atascada, muévela suavemente de lado a lado mientras jalas. No uses fuerza excesiva para no dañarla.",
      "title": "Desmonta la manija del grifo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa una llave ajustable para girar en sentido antihorario la tuerca de empaque que sostiene el cartucho o la válvula. Retírala con cuidado y guárdala en un lugar seguro.",
      "title": "Retira la tuerca de empaque"
    },
    {
      "text": "Jala el cartucho o la válvula hacia afuera en línea recta. Toma nota de su posición antes de retirarlo o toma una foto, para instalarlo correctamente después.",
      "title": "Extrae el cartucho o la válvula"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lleva el cartucho a una ferretería para conseguir uno idéntico, o busca el número de modelo del grifo. Compra también empaques de repuesto del mismo tamaño si están desgastados.",
      "title": "Consigue las piezas de repuesto"
    },
    {
      "text": "Inserta el nuevo cartucho en la misma dirección que el original. Debe quedar firme y alineado con las ranuras del cuerpo del grifo. Compara con tu foto si tienes dudas.",
      "title": "Instala el nuevo cartucho"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca la tuerca de empaque y gírala en sentido horario con la mano primero. Luego apriétala con la llave ajustable. No aprietes de más para no dañar el rosco.",
      "title": "Vuelve a colocar la tuerca"
    },
    {
      "text": "Desliza la manija sobre el cartucho y alinea los orificios con el tornillo. Inserta y aprieta el tornillo, luego coloca la tapa decorativa presionando hasta que encaje con un clic.",
      "title": "Reensambla la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abre lentamente las llaves de paso girándolas en sentido antihorario. Luego abre el grifo y observa si gotea. Si el goteo desapareció, ¡la reparación fue exitosa!",
      "title": "Abre el agua y verifica"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Make sure your document is open and you've made at least one change. The title bar at the top of the window typically shows an asterisk (*) or indicator next to the file name when there are unsaved changes.",
      "title": "Confirm Your Document Is Open"
    },
    {
      "text": "Move your mouse to the top-left corner of the screen and click **File**. The File menu will open, showing document management options like New, Open, and Save.",
      "title": "Click the File Menu"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Save** in the menu list. If this is a new document, a Save As dialog will appear. If the file already has a name, it saves immediately. You should see a brief progress indicator or the title bar asterisk disappear.",
      "title": "Select Save"
    },
    {
      "text": "If a **Save As** dialog appeared, navigate to your desired folder using the left panel or address bar. Double-click a folder to open it, then confirm the location shown in the address bar before saving.",
      "title": "Choose a Save Location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check the **File name** field at the bottom of the dialog. Click it to clear the default name, then type a clear, descriptive name for your document. Avoid special characters like `/`, `\\`, or `*`.",
      "title": "Enter a File Name"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the **Save** button in the bottom-right corner of the dialog. The dialog will close and you'll return to your document. The title bar will now show your chosen file name without an asterisk.",
      "title": "Confirm and Save"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at the title bar at the top of the window. It should display your file name *without* an asterisk or unsaved indicator. This confirms your document has been saved successfully.",
